    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275901\">@Jules Hedges</span> <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275902\">@Giorgos Bakirtzis</span> Is a Markov game something like \"a game internal to the category where morphisms are markov kernels\"?</p>",
        "id": 218323501,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1606759899
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><em>Sort of</em>, but the distinguishing property of a Markov game is that players have bounded memory, they can only observe the current state instead of the entire history of the play - that's the game theoretic version of the Markov property</p>",
        "id": 218333070,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1606764220
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's pushing it to say that there's a general one-size-fits-all definition of \"games over a category\", but to the extent that there is, games over the category of Markov kernels describe extensive form games of imperfect information with Bayesian Nash equilibria. (There's some handwaving involved there)</p>",
        "id": 218333356,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1606764358
    },
